******
[2] Santa Cruz County
Date: Thu 31 Aug 2017 7:20 PM PDT
Source: Santa Cruz Sentinel [edited]
http://www.santacruzsentinel.com/article/NE/20170831/NEWS/170839935


From a handful of cases in April 2017, hepatitis A has spread to 65 people, many of them homeless and many of them drug users, and Dr Arnold Leff, Santa Cruz County health officer, has been leading an effort to contain the disease.

So far:
- 850 vaccinations have been given.
- Vaccination clinics are ongoing at a half-dozen locations, including the jail and the emergency department at Dignity Health Dominican Hospital.
- Vaccine outreach is targeting parks and camp sites where those infected spent time.
- Plans are being made for clinics to vaccinate county staff and others at risk of contracting the highly contagious disease.

The outbreak has affected about twice as many men as women, 62 percent being under age 40, according to Leff's data. About 80 percent reported being homeless, 75 percent reported illicit drug use, and 64 percent indicated drug use and homelessness, Leff's figures show.

Hepatitis A spreads when a person eats or drinks something contaminated with the hepatitis A virus. If someone who is infected doesn't wash his hands well after using the bathroom and then touches food, the disease can be passed to others who eat that food. Male homosexuals having sex with an infected person is another way to contract the disease.

Dominican Hospital reports seeing more than 30 cases of hepatitis A since spring.. "It is really concerning," said Dr John Kaufmann, an infectious disease specialist who has worked at Dominican Hospital for 12 years. "We have 2 cases a year normally." When people come to the emergency room for other reasons other than hepatitis A, those identified at high risk of contracting hepatitis A are offered the vaccine. Close to 100 vaccinations have been given, Kaufmann said.

Leff's data show a spike of 11 cases reported in one week in mid-July 2017, then dropping, but Kauffman said he doesn't know if the outbreak is declining. "We want to assume the worst," he said. "We want to make sure people get the vaccination. Caregivers, drug users, people who are homeless, anyone who wants the vaccine should get it." A 2nd dose of vaccine is needed after 6 months, he said. He said the vaccine is for people who are not infected.

People who are infected can recover in 6 months with rest, avoiding alcohol and drinking plenty of water. But there can be complications.

In San Diego County, 15 people have died from hepatitis A, but health officials have not found a common source of food, beverages or drugs to trigger the outbreak. "We're doing everything we can to protect people that come into our jail," said Sgt. Chris Clark, spokesman for the sheriff's office. "It's affecting a vulnerable population in our community and we understand that,"

[Byline: Jondi Gumz]

