[The number of cases of diagnosed hepatitis A (HAV) in San Diego County in southern California has continued to increase. As of [Tue 29 Aug 2017], the San Diego county case load and the trends are:

Date / Cases / Hospitalized (percentage) / Deaths (percentage)
5 Apr 2017 / 39 / 33 (85) / 1 (3)
4 May 2017 / 80 / 66 (83) / 3 (4)
31 May 2017 / 133 / 103 (80) / 3 (2)
12 Jun 2017 / 160 / 120 (75) / 4 (2.5)
27 Jun 2017 / 196 / 142 (72) / 4 (2)
26 Jul 2017 / 275 / 194 (71) / 7 (2.5)
1 Aug 2017 / 295 / 202 (68) / 10 (3.4)
8 Aug 2017 / 312 / 215 (69) / 10 (3.2)
15 Aug 2017 / 333 / 232 (70) / 11 (3.3)
22 Aug 2017 / 352 / 246 (70) / 14 (4)
29 Aug 2017 / 378 / 263 (70) / 15 (4)

This week [week of Sun 27 Aug 2017], the San Diego county authorities have recommended HAV immunization for food handlers, a rational idea that should have been routine policy in the USA previously (see discussion in Hepatitis A - USA (23): (CA) fatal Archive Number: 20170829.5281598) and now almost 400 cases and 15 deaths into the outbreak, hand washing are being provided for the homeless. Additionally, street-cleaning crews shooting high-pressure water spiked with bleach to remove "all feces, blood, bodily fluids or contaminated surfaces," although it is not clear that such contaminated surfaces exist and if they do, it should not take a HAV outbreak to clean them up.

It is interesting that San Diego County and Santa Cruz County are about 400 miles (644 km) apart, with San Diego in southernmost California bordering Mexico and Santa Cruz just south of San Francisco. Clearly the underlying potential risk factors seem similar and it would be quite interesting to know if the genetic evaluation of the viruses from both counties, if available, is identical or not. Another ongoing outbreak of hepatitis A, in eastern Michigan, has been reported to be genetically different from the San Diego cohort.

The state of California can be located on the HealthMap/ProMED-mail interactive map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5291024,4262. A county map can be seen at http://geology.com/county-map/california-county-map.gif. - Mod.LL
